<h1>Spanish Immersion Guatemala</h1><p>&nbsp;Katherine Ragzdale shares her Spanish language experience in Guatemala, where she participated in a homestay and immersion program in the city of Quetzaltenango, also known as Xela. During her stay, she lived with a local family and practiced her developing Spanish skills in everyday conversations with Claudia Huipz and her children. This daily interaction allowed her to apply what she learned in class to real-life situations, strengthening both her confidence and fluency.</p><iframe width="100%" height="550" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Lv4_hcWwZ7s" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p>&nbsp;She studied Spanish for several weeks at Casa Xelajú, a language school based in Quetzaltenango. One of the main academic focuses she highlights is practicing the subjunctive mood, which she found especially valuable. Through consistent study and guided instruction, she feels that her ability to write in Spanish improved significantly, enabling her to express herself more clearly and effectively.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Katherine also reflects on the structure of her classes and the overall learning environment. She describes being part of a group of around eleven students, which created opportunities to exchange experiences and build friendships. The social aspect of the program enriched her learning, as students could support one another while navigating the challenges of acquiring a new language.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The experience extended well beyond the classroom. Living with a host family meant participating in daily routines such as visiting the market and sharing meals. Although certain restrictions affected how food could be shared at the time, the immersion into local life remained an essential part of the program. These everyday interactions provided meaningful cultural exposure and constant language practice.</p>
<p>&nbsp;She also discusses the advantages of in-person learning compared to virtual classes, expressing a clear preference for being physically present. Being in Guatemala allowed her to dedicate her time and attention fully to studying Spanish without the distractions of her usual environment. Overall, she describes the experience as very positive, emphasizing the personal growth that came from having the time, space, and supportive environment to focus entirely on learning the language.</p>
